The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      The City Diary
                Traffic was severely affected across Calcutta because of four demonstrations on Monday. Nearly 4,500 supporters of the All India United Trade Union Centre, the labour wing of the SUCI, took out a rally in the afternoon from Raja Subodh Mullick Square to Rani Rashmoni Avenue to protest the rise in the prices of essential commodities. They also urged people to make the proposed general strike on September 7 a success. Police arrested 1,225 protesters.																																																																																		   Around the same time, 30-odd PTTI teachers demonstrated on Brabourne Road, adjacent to gate 1A of Writers Buildings. Around 30 protesters were arrested and taken to Lalbazar.  Also in the afternoon, around 100 auto operators put up a blockade on Beleghata Main Road protesting the introduction of a route from Sealdah railway station.  In the evening, traffic came to a halt on Belgachia Road after members of a Durga puja committee blocked the road for not being allowed to erect a pandal on a private land. The blockade continued for half an hour.     Ujjwal Dey Chowdhury, 26, was arrested on Monday in Burtolla for allegedly stealing a laptop and Rs 1,500 from a north Calcutta house on August 20. The booty was found in his possession. In another incident, police arrested Rana Hassan in Maniktala and recovered two cellphones and Rs 10,000 which he had stolen from the house of theatre actor and director Rudraprasad Sengupta on August 14.    Dilip Rai, 27, was shot dead at Kankinara Bazar, on the northern fringes of the city, when he was heading for the market on Monday morning. Cops said three unidentified men had come on a motorcycle and fired at him.    More than 100 residents of Kazipara in Howrah demonstrated in front of Vidyasagar Setu toll plaza between 3.30pm and 4pm on Monday to protest cops fleecing truck drivers. The police said a bike-borne youth had hit a truck that had been stopped by a traffic sergeant to check relevant papers. As news spread about the incident, residents rushed to the spot and blocked the road.     Clinton Mys, 21, a resident of Temple Street in Chandni Chowk, died after he jumped from one of the top floors of a multi-storeyed building in the locality.     Three persons died in an accident on Amtala Road in Bishnupur on the southern fringes of the city on Monday. Haran Sardar, Sheikh Saiyad Mollah and Chunnu Sheikh were in a Joynagar-bound Matador that had collided with a Calcutta-bound truck.     Five labourers were injured after a part of the roof of Bargram Anchal Vidyapith in Howrah collapsed around 10.30am on Monday. Police said five labourers were working on the campus when the roof collapsed. They were taken to a local hospital.     A ragpicker was run over by a bus on New CIT Road near Poddar Court around 7pm on Monday. Local residents broke windowpanes of three buses and tried to set one bus on fire. Cops brought the situation under control.     A book of condolences for Gnter Wehrmann, the German consul-general who died on Sunday, will be kept at the office of the consulate general of the Federal Republic of Germany at 1 Hastings Park Road, Alipore, on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday from 10am to 3pm.            
